Broadcast joins.

A normal join shuffles both sides by the join key, which is expensive for large tables. A broadcast join avoids that — it ships the smaller side to every executor, eliminating the shuffle entirely.

Spark auto-broadcasts when one side's estimated size is below the auto-broadcast-join-threshold, which defaults to ten megabytes but is often tuned to a hundred or more. So for the bank, joining fifty billion card transactions against a five-megabyte merchant-categories lookup auto-broadcasts naturally. When statistics are stale or you know better than the optimiser, you can force it by wrapping the small side in broadcast, or with a broadcast hint in sequel.

But it can backfire. Broadcasting a side that's larger than driver memory blows up the driver. So cap the broadcast threshold at roughly the size of the largest small table you actually have.

One more thing worth knowing — adaptive query execution, which we cover in the optimization notebook, can promote a regular sort-merge join to a broadcast join at runtime, once it sees the real partition sizes, even if the planner's statistics said otherwise.
